Question 3: What is the average price of all the vehicles? the median price? and the deciles? Displays these on a plot of the distribution of vehicle prices.

There are outliers skewing the data that originate from errors from webscraping. Remove the outliers to gain a better understanding of the data.

In [9]:
price_frequency = subset(vposts$price, vposts$price > 10 & vposts$price<= 1e5)
mean_price_frequency = mean(price_frequency)
median_price_frequency = median(price_frequency)
dec_price_frequency = quantile(price_frequency, seq(0,1, by=.1), na.rm = TRUE)
hist(price_frequency, seq(0, 1e5, by=2000), main = "Frequency of Automobiles Based on Price", xlab = "Automobile Prices", ylab = "Automobile Frequency")
abline(v = mean_price_frequency, col = "Dark Blue")
abline(v = median_price_frequency, col = "Dark Green")
abline(v = dec_price_frequency, col = "Pink")
legend(7e4,5000, c("Mean", "Median", "Deciles"), lty=c(1,1,1), lwd=c(2.5,2.5,2.5), col=c("Dark Blue", "Dark Green", "Pink"))
label = c("mean","median")
value = c(mean_price_frequency,median_price_frequency)
rbind(label,value)
labelmean median
value9920.761270525256950

Question 5: Display the relationship between fuel type and vehicle type. Does this depend on transmission type?

In [12]:
splitted_trans = split(vposts, vposts$transmission)
Tables = lapply(splitted_trans, function(df) table(df$fuel, df$type)) 
par(mfrow = c(1,3))
types = dimnames(Tables$automatic)[[1]]
dimnames(Tables$automatic)[[1]] = rep(NA, length(types))
mosaicplot(Tables$automatic, las = 2, main = "", xlab ="Transmisson: Automatic", ylab = "Car Type", cex.axis = .9)
at = seq(0, 1, len = length(types))
axis(3, c(0.33, .37, .64, .93, .97), types, las = 2)

typesm = dimnames(Tables$manual)[[1]]
dimnames(Tables$manual)[[1]] = rep(NA, length(typesm))
mosaicplot(Tables$manual, las = 2, main = "", xlab ="Transmission: Manual", cex.axis = .9)
at = seq(0, 1, len = length(types))
axis(3, c(0.35, .37, .64, .96, .98), types)

typeso = dimnames(Tables$other)[[1]]
dimnames(Tables$other)[[1]] = rep(NA, length(typeso))
mosaicplot(Tables$other, las = 2, main = "", xlab ="Transmission: Other", cex.axis = .9)
at = seq(0, 1, len = length(typeso))
axis(3, c(0.33, .36, .64, .9, .97), types, las = 2)

There is an easily apparent difference within the area of the boxes depending on the transmission type. Vehicles that use other types of transmission use significantly more of the other type of gasoline than automatic or manual. On the other hand, manual is more evenly distributed between the various car types and gasoline types than the other two with the exception of trucks using significantly more diesel. Automatic and Other transmissions use more gasoline within SUV and Sedan types than manual.

Question 9: What are the three most common makes of cars in each city for "sale by owner" and for "sale by dealer"? Are they similar or quite different?

In [19]:
by_owner = subset(vposts, vposts$byOwner == TRUE)
counts_owner = table(by_owner$city, by_owner$maker)
by_dealer = subset(vposts, vposts$byOwner == FALSE)
counts_dealer = table(by_dealer$city, by_dealer$maker)

Top 3 makes by owner

In [20]:
top3_makes = function(city_counts) {
  top3_by_owner = order(city_counts, decreasing = TRUE)[1:3]
  colnames(counts_owner)[top3_by_owner]
}

apply(counts_owner, 1, top3_makes)
top3_makes = function(city_counts) {
  top3_by_dealer = order(city_counts, decreasing = TRUE)[1:3]
  colnames(counts_dealer)[top3_by_dealer]
}

Question 11: Plot the locations of the posts on a map? What do you notice?

In [28]:
library(maps)
par(mfrow = c(1,1))
map('state')
map('state', c("Massachusetts", "Illinois","Colorado", "Nevada", "New York","California"), add = TRUE, fill = TRUE, col = "red")
points(vposts$long, vposts$lat, col = "Dark green", pch=".", title ("Map of Automobile Location Postings"))

In the map the red states are the states in which the cities of interest are located. The green dots represent a single posting from that location. Looking at the map individuals posted cars in cities that were far away from their actual location. While most of the posting are centered around the city they were targeting, there were a significant amount that were in surrounding states and even non neighboring states. Therefore, this graph reveals that people lie about their location in order to increase the chances of selling their car.

Question 12: Summarize the distribution of fuel type, drive, transmission, and vehicle type. Find a good way to display this information.

In [29]:
par(mfrow = c(3,1))
splitted_bydrive = split(vposts, updyearvposts$drive)
Table_bydrive_fuel_transmission = lapply(splitted_bydrive, function(df) table(df$fuel, df$transmission)) 
mosaicplot(Table_bydrive_fuel_transmission$`4wd`, las = 1, main= "                    Transmission Based on Fuel Type: 4wd", cex.axis = .9)
mosaicplot(Table_bydrive_fuel_transmission$fwd, las = 1, main= "                    Transmission Based on Fuel Type: fwd", cex.axis = .9)
mosaicplot(Table_bydrive_fuel_transmission$rwd, las = 1, main= "                    Transmission Based on Fuel Type: rwd", cex.axis = .9)
Table_bydrive_fuel_type = lapply(splitted_bydrive, function(df) table(df$fuel, df$type)) 
mosaicplot(Table_bydrive_fuel_type$`4wd`, las = 1, main= "                    Car Type Based on Fuel Type: 4wd", cex = .9)
mosaicplot(Table_bydrive_fuel_type$fwd, las = 1, main= "                    Car Type Based on Fuel Type: fwd", cex = .9)
mosaicplot(Table_bydrive_fuel_type$rwd, las = 1, main= "                    Car Type Based on Fuel Type: rwd", cex = .9)
Table_bydrive_transmission_type = lapply(splitted_bydrive, function(df) table(df$transmission, df$type)) 
mosaicplot(Table_bydrive_transmission_type$`4wd`, las = 1, main= "                    Car Type Based on Transmission: 4wd", cex.axis = .9)
mosaicplot(Table_bydrive_transmission_type$fwd, las = 1, main= "                    Car Type Based on Transmission: fwd", cex.axis = .9)
mosaicplot(Table_bydrive_transmission_type$rwd, las = 1, main= "                    Car Type Based on Transmission: rwd", cex.axis = .9)

Examining the above graph 4wd and rwd are relatively similar based on fuel type. Both these types of fuel follow a similar distribution with only slight variations that can be attributed to chance seen in gas and diesel. These types of drive are significantly different than fwd, seen in the lack of diesel cars with fwd compared to rwd and 4wd, as well as fwd, having more gas and hybrid cars. Rwd is also significantly different than fwd and 4wd within electric cars. Transmission type has a slight deviation between the fuel distributions, however this difference is minimal and can be attributed to random chance, except for the biggest deviation between 4wd and fwd in which there appears to be a slight significance. Fuel type is heavily affected by transmission where a majority of cars drive automatic, across all transmission types and gas is the main source of fuel, which makes sense since automatic cars and gas fueled cars are the most prevalent cars in the world.

Condition on Odometer

In [40]:
plot(important_conditions, Fix_odometer_vposts$odometer, main = "Miles Traveled Based on the Condition of Car", xlab = "Car Condition", ylab = "Miles Traveled")
mean_odometer_condition = mean(Fix_odometer_vposts$odometer)
median_odometer_condition = median(Fix_odometer_vposts$odometer)
abline(h = mean_odometer_condition, col = "Dark Blue")
abline(h = median_odometer_condition, col = "Red")
legend("topright",100, c("Mean", "Median"), lty=c(1,1), lwd=c(2.5,2.5), col=c("Dark Blue", "Red"))

Based on the box and whisker plot above the better the condition of a car the fewer miles traveled. This makes sense since the more you travel with a car the more used it becomes. This trend continues as a car becomes worse quality except for used and salvage. The option used is not descriptive and therefore people could have selected used for their cars even if they had minimal use. Salvage, on the other hand, usually happens when a car becomes totaled or too expensive to fix. Totaled cars can happen at any time during the lifespan of a car due to the unpredictability of accidents, seen in the wide range of data points within the salvage column.

Condition on Price

In [41]:
Fix_odometer_vposts_price = subset(Fix_odometer_vposts, Fix_odometer_vposts$price <= 2e5)
important_conditions_price = ordered(as.character(Fix_odometer_vposts_price$condition),  levels = c("new", "like new", "excellent", "good", "fair", "used", "salvage"))
plot(important_conditions_price, Fix_odometer_vposts_price$price, main = "Price Based on the Condition of Car", xlab = "Car Condition", ylab = "Price")
mean_price_condition = mean(Fix_odometer_vposts_price$price)
median_price_condition = median(Fix_odometer_vposts_price$price)
abline(h = mean_price_condition, col = "Dark Blue")
abline(h = median_price_condition, col = "Red")
legend("topright",100, c("Mean", "Median"), lty=c(1,1), lwd=c(2.5,2.5), col=c("Dark Blue", "Red"))

Price follows a similar distribution to miles traveled, which is a result of the linear relationship between these two factors. The main difference is seen in the new column where new cars are actually lower in price than cars tagged as like new. This is most likely due to the fact that new and like new cars can be seen as similar options, meaning that these two options could be grouped together. As the condition of a car decreases so does the price, besides used cars, which presents a statistical anomaly. As mentioned in the previous graph, the used option is ambiguous and so people could have driven their car once and then put it for sale as used.

Condition on Age

In [42]:
plot(important_conditions_price, Fix_odometer_vposts_price$Car_age, main = "Age Based on the Condition of Car", xlab = "Car Condition", ylab = "Car Age")
mean_age_condition = mean(Fix_odometer_vposts_price$Car_age)
median_age_condition = median(Fix_odometer_vposts_price$Car_age)
abline(h = mean_age_condition, col = "Dark Blue")
abline(h = median_age_condition, col = "Red")
legend("topright",100, c("Mean", "Median"), lty=c(1,1), lwd=c(2.5,2.5), col=c("Dark Blue", "Red"))

This graph follows a similar distribution as the above options where the better the car condition the younger the car. This graph reveals that like new cars are typically younger than new cars and most surprisingly used cars are the newest cars. Thus, since used cars are typically the youngest this explains why used cars have the lowest odometer readings and also the most expensive. Consequently, there is mislabeling in this data set where cars labeled as used could statistically be newer than new cars.
